The '''stratum intermedium''' in a [[tooth development|developing tooth]] is a layer of two or three [[cells (biology)|cells]] between the [[inner enamel epithelium]] and the newly forming cells of the [[stellate reticulum]]. It first appears during the early bell stage of tooth development, at around the 14th week of intrauterine life. The stratum intermedium has a notably high [[alkaline phosphatase]] activity.  This layer, along with the inner enamel epithelium, is responsible for the [[tooth enamel]] [[amelogenesis|formation]]. It is a part of the dental (enamel) organ.

